      acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Take melatonin-based sleep gummies 30-60 minutes before your intended bedtime. This timing aligns with melatonin\'s pharmacokinetics, allowing blood levels to peak as you want to fall asleep. Magnesium-based sleep gummies can be taken 1-2 hours before bed.' },
    },
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'Do sleep gummies work better than melatonin pills?',
      acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'The active ingredients are equally effective in both forms. Gummies may absorb slightly faster because they begin breaking down in the mouth (sublingual absorption). The primary advantage of gummies is compliance — people are more likely to take them consistently because of the pleasant taste.' },
    },
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'Can children take sleep gummies?',
      acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Some melatonin gummies are formulated for children (typically ages 4+), but pediatric use should always be supervised by a pediatrician. The American Academy of Pediatrics recommends addressing sleep hygiene first before supplementing. Children should use lower doses (0.5-1mg) and only under medical guidance.' },
    },
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'Are there side effects from sleep gummies?',
      acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Common side effects include next-day drowsiness, headaches, and vivid dreams. Less common side effects include nausea, dizziness, and irritability. These are more likely at higher doses (5mg+). If you experience persistent side effects, reduce your dosage or discontinue use and consult a healthcare provider.' },
    },
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'What is the difference between melatonin and magnesium sleep gummies?',
      acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Melatonin directly signals your brain that it is time to sleep by mimicking the hormone your body produces at night. Magnesium works indirectly by activating the parasympathetic nervous system, relaxing muscles, and calming neural activity. Magnesium is better for people who feel physically tense at bedtime, while melatonin is better for circadian rhythm issues like jet lag or shift work.' },
    },
  ],
};
