    <!-- FAQ -->
    <section>
      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions About Sleep Gummies</h2>

      <details class="fq">
        <summary>Are sleep gummies safe to take every night?</summary>
        <p>Most sleep gummies containing melatonin are considered safe for short-term nightly use (up to 2-3 months) in healthy adults. However, the American Academy of Sleep Medicine recommends using melatonin supplements as a short-term aid rather than a permanent solution. Long-term use has not been extensively studied, so it is best to consult your healthcare provider if you plan to take sleep gummies for more than 3 months consecutively. Consider periodic breaks — such as 3 weeks on, 1 week off — to prevent reliance.</p>
      </details>

      <details class="fq">
        <summary>Can you become dependent on melatonin gummies?</summary>
        <p>Melatonin is not physically addictive and does not create the chemical dependency associated with prescription sleep medications like benzodiazepines or Z-drugs. Your body does not develop a tolerance to melatonin in the pharmacological sense. However, some people develop a psychological reliance — they feel unable to sleep without taking a gummy, even though their body would produce melatonin naturally. Cycling your usage and maintaining strong sleep hygiene habits helps prevent this pattern.</p>
      </details>

      <details class="fq">
        <summary>What is the best melatonin dosage for sleep?</summary>
        <p>Research from MIT suggests that <strong>0.5mg to 3mg</strong> is the effective range for most adults. The key insight is that higher doses are not necessarily more effective — a 0.3mg dose raised blood melatonin to normal nighttime levels in the MIT study, while a 3mg dose raised it far above natural levels without additional sleep benefits. Start with the lowest available dose and increase only if you do not notice improvement after 3-5 nights.</p>
      </details>

      <details class="fq">
        <summary>When should I take sleep gummies for the best results?</summary>
        <p>Take melatonin-based sleep gummies <strong>30 to 60 minutes before your intended bedtime</strong>. This allows the melatonin to reach peak blood concentration as you want to fall asleep. Taking melatonin too early (2+ hours before bed) or too late (right as you lie down) reduces its effectiveness. For magnesium-based gummies like Moon Juice Magnesi-Om, take them 1-2 hours before bed to allow the relaxation effects to build gradually.</p>
      </details>

      <details class="fq">
        <summary>Do sleep gummies work better than melatonin pills or capsules?</summary>
        <p>The active ingredients are equally effective in both delivery formats. Gummies may absorb slightly faster because they begin breaking down in the mouth through sublingual absorption, but the difference is marginal — perhaps 5-10 minutes faster onset. The real advantage of gummies is <strong>compliance</strong>. Studies show that people are significantly more likely to take supplements consistently when they enjoy the experience, and the pleasant taste of gummies drives higher adherence rates than pills or capsules.</p>
      </details>

      <details class="fq">
        <summary>Can children take sleep gummies?</summary>
        <p>Some melatonin gummies are specifically formulated for children (typically ages 4 and older), but pediatric use should <strong>always</strong> be supervised by a pediatrician. The American Academy of Pediatrics recommends addressing sleep hygiene and behavioral factors first — consistent bedtime routines, limited screen time, and a cool dark room — before considering supplementation. If a pediatrician approves melatonin, children should use lower doses (0.5-1mg) and take it only as needed, not nightly.</p>
      </details>

      <details class="fq">
        <summary>Are there side effects from taking sleep gummies?</summary>
        <p>The most commonly reported side effects include next-day drowsiness, headaches, vivid or unusual dreams, and mild nausea. These are more likely at higher doses (5mg and above). Less common side effects include dizziness, short-term feelings of depression, mild tremor, and irritability. If you experience persistent side effects, <strong>reduce your dosage first</strong> — many people find that cutting from 3mg to 1mg eliminates side effects while maintaining sleep benefits. Discontinue use and consult a healthcare provider if side effects persist at the lowest dose.</p>
      </details>

      <details class="fq">
        <summary>What is the difference between melatonin and magnesium for sleep?</summary>
        <p>Melatonin and magnesium work through entirely different mechanisms. <strong>Melatonin</strong> directly signals your brain that it is time to sleep by mimicking the hormone your pineal gland produces in response to darkness. It is most effective for falling asleep faster. <strong>Magnesium</strong> works indirectly by activating the parasympathetic nervous system, relaxing muscles, and calming overactive neural circuits. Magnesium is better for people who feel physically tense or mentally wired at bedtime. Some people find that combining both — melatonin for sleep onset and magnesium for physical relaxation — delivers the best results.</p>
      </details>
    </section>

